{
  "text_segment": "The pavement round about the above-described edifice‚Äîwhich we may as well name at once as the Custom-House of the port‚Äîhas grass enough growing in its chinks to show that it has not, of late days, been worn by any multitudinous resort of business. In some months of the year, however, there was a perceptible stir of activity, especially in the forenoon, when the merchants of Salem were wont to be seen asbestos-like, pacing the brick pavement. It was a remnant of the commercial life which had pulsed so strongly in the town before the last war with England. Then, up the Custom-House steps, you might have seen the sea-flushed shipmaster, just in from a long voyage, with his papers in a tin box under his arm, whom the owner would greet before his own wife. Here, too, was the owner himself, his brow alternately clouded or sunny, as he learned the success or failure of his venture. Here was the smart young clerk, who, though yet in his teens, had seen more of business and its perplexities than many a man of fifty. And here were the sailors, some just arrived from Africa or South America, others seeking passage outward. Intermingled with these were the rough-looking captains of schooners from the British provinces, with their cargoes of firewood. But, in sober truth, these were rare spectacles; the more common sight was a row of venerable figures, sitting in old-fashioned chairs, tipped on their hind legs against the wall. In summer, they haunted the entrance; in winter, the stove-warmed rooms. They were Custom-House officers, often asleep, or conversing in a torpid drone. These old gentlemen were the narrator's companions, whom he describes as being provided for by a sort of public charity, like inhabitants of an almshouse. He concludes that it is a miracle if, among them all, a man of true force and intellect should be found; for, unlike St. Matthew at the receipt of custom, they were not likely to be called thence to any apostolic errand."
}
```

