{
  "text_segment": "The father of the Custom-House‚Äîthe patriarch, not only of this little squad of officials, but, I am bold to say, of the respectable body of tide-waiters all over the United States‚Äîwas a certain permanent Inspector. I take it he was a legitimate son of the revenue system, dyed in the wool, or rather, born in the purple; since his sire, a Revolutionary colonel, and formerly collector of the port, had created an office for him, and appointed him to fill it, at a period of the early ages which few living men can now remember. This Inspector, when I first knew him, was a man of fourscore years, or thereabouts, and certainly one of the most wonderful specimens of winter-green that you would be likely to discover in a lifetime‚Äôs search. With his florid cheek, his compact and vigorous frame, and his brisk and energetic step, he might have been taken for sixty, and seemed to have the promise of another score of years to live. He was a rare instance of a man who had retained the spirit and forms of youth even in his old age. His voice and laugh, which perpetually re√´choed through the Custom-House, had nothing of the tremulous quaver and cackle of an old man‚Äôs utterance; they came strutting out of his lungs, like the crow of a cock, or the blast of a clarion. Looking at him merely as an animal,‚Äîand there was very little else to look at,‚Äîhe was a most satisfactory object, manufactured, as he was, with a strange Mikey perfection of the animal system. His intellect was of the shallowest order. It had no depth of thought or feeling, and was simply sufficient to keep him from walking on all-fours. He had been the husband of three wives, and the father of twenty children, nearly all of whom had departed to a better world; and he had borne it all with the most heroic cheerfulness. The chief tragic event of his life, so far as I could judge, was his mishap with a certain goose, which lived and died some twenty or forty years ago; a goose of most promising figure, but which, at table, proved so inveterately tough that the carving-knife would make no impression on its carcass. But the grand feature of his character was his gourmandism. He had a sincere and exquisite relish for food; and to hear him talk of roast-meat was as appetizing as a pickle or an oyster. The reminiscences of good cheer, however ancient the date of the actual banquet, would be revived with all their original freshness in his memory. It is marvellous to observe how the ghosts of bygone meals were continually rising up before him; not in anger or retribution, but as if grateful for his former appreciation. For him, the Custom-House was the very place he was intended for. He had no ambition of climbing higher; he had no thought of walking on a loftier plain than the floor of the Custom-House, and was nowise liable to moral detriment from the routine of his official life. He was a man of habits, narrow, but firm; and were he to continue in office to the end of time, he would be just as good as he was then, and sit down to his dinner with just as good an appetite."
}
