  "text_segment": "It is my belief, however, that, had I attempted a different order of composition, my faculties would not have been found so pointless and inefficacious. I might, for instance, have contented myself with writing out the narratives of a veteran shipmaster, one of my colleagues in the Custom-House, or I might have tried to spiritualize the daily life that surrounded me, finding the deeper meaning in what appeared to be merely dull and commonplace. The fault was mine; the page of life that was spread out before me was a 'better book' than I had genius or wisdom to read. Instead, my former pleasure in writing had become a hopeless toil, and I had ceased to be a writer of mediocre tales to become a Surveyor of the Revenue, and a reasonably competent one at that.\n\nThis experience leads me to a reflection on the effects of public office. It is a strange but undeniable fact that, to a man who has leaned on the mighty arm of the Republic, it is seldom possible afterwards to stand upright on his own feet. The man of true talent who wins a public appointment is fortunate if he is ejected before the system has had time to rust into his soul. He who is ejected, though it may be for his own good, is generally a ruined man, rarely recovering the forfeited powers that might have made him independent. He continues to look for another prop to lean on, for the persistent and hallucinatory hope of being restored to office saps the will for any other enterprise. Uncle Sam's gold seems to have an enchantment like that of the Devil's wages; it is paid you for your better attributes, and when you have bartered them away, the gold is gone, and you are left with nothing."
